used a prototyping tool before,

00:00:14.430 --> 00:00:16.210
or one of the tools
maybe listed up here?

00:00:16.210 --> 00:00:17.291
Just raise your hand.

00:00:17.291 --> 00:00:17.790
Oh, my.

00:00:17.790 --> 00:00:18.905
That's awesome.

00:00:18.905 --> 00:00:20.164
I actually didn't expect that.

00:00:20.164 --> 00:00:21.330
That's really, really great.

00:00:21.330 --> 00:00:24.390
I'm super excited to
facilitate a conversation

00:00:24.390 --> 00:00:27.430
about these tools and
why they matter for us.

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:29.762
And actually, while
we're talking,

00:00:29.762 --> 00:00:31.720
I want you to think about
questions at the end,

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:34.340
because I will say there's
not been a lot of questions.

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:36.340
So just prepare
now, and write down

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:38.099
little doodles or
notes of things.

00:00:38.099 --> 00:00:39.890
I'm totally going to
just hope that there's

00:00:39.890 --> 00:00:42.310
amazing questions afterward.

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:43.960
The first thing I
wanted to point out

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:47.450
was that you'll notice on
this panel there's not really

00:00:47.450 --> 00:00:49.912
any representation from
traditional design tools

00:00:49.912 --> 00:00:51.120
you might have thought about.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:51.620
Right?

00:00:51.620 --> 00:00:54.110
There's not anyone here from
something like Photoshop

00:00:54.110 --> 00:00:58.120
or Sketch, even though we spend
a lot of time in those tools.

00:00:58.120 --> 00:01:00.990
These are all people who've
created interactive tools,

00:01:00.990 --> 00:01:04.580
yet we still chose to call the
panel Design Tooling and not

00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:06.640
something like Prototyping
to kind of make

00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:09.415
a statement about where we
think these tools are headed.

00:01:09.415 --> 00:01:11.040
We really think it's
the next evolution

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:13.750
of the medium of the tools
we use and what we work on.

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:17.400
So I think we've used static
mockmaking tools for a while,

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:19.024
and they worked
really, really well

00:01:19.024 --> 00:01:20.690
in a world where we
were creating things

00:01:20.690 --> 00:01:24.090
like business cards and
book covers and posters.

00:01:24.090 --> 00:01:27.190
But now with our devices,
we touch, we drag,

00:01:27.190 --> 00:01:30.020
we swipe, we play,
in some cases,

00:01:30.020 --> 00:01:32.400
we speak with our devices.

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:35.280
And yet we're using tools
that don't necessarily

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:36.040
represent that.

00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:36.540
Right?

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:38.750
We're using these
flat, static tools,

00:01:38.750 --> 00:01:41.961
and I think it's mostly
because it's easier.

00:01:41.961 --> 00:01:42.460
Right?

00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:45.420
There's not really much
of a better option.

00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:47.470
It's just kind of the
best that we have.

00:01:47.470 --> 00:01:49.090
And I think what
I'm excited about is

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:50.610
I think that's starting
to change, thanks a lot

00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:52.050
of the people you see here.

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:53.550
So I think a common
scenario that

00:01:53.550 --> 00:01:56.000
might sound kind of
familiar to many of you

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.270
is you're in a meeting room--
some combination of maybe

00:01:59.270 --> 00:02:02.010
product managers,
engineers, and designers--

00:02:02.010 --> 00:02:05.300
and you're looking up at a
screen in some kind of room,

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:08.460
and that screen has a
picture of a phone on it.

00:02:08.460 --> 00:02:10.720
And that picture has a bunch
of pictures inside of it,

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:12.080
and you're kind of
clicking through a bunch

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:14.810
of different mockups, and you're
making some pretty important

00:02:14.810 --> 00:02:16.319
decisions at that
point sometimes.

00:02:16.319 --> 00:02:18.110
You're starting to kind
of critique things,

00:02:18.110 --> 00:02:20.540
the way things look, the
way things are placed,

00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:22.130
but it kind of feels productive.

00:02:22.130 --> 00:02:22.630
You know?

00:02:22.630 --> 00:02:23.630
You're making decisions.

00:02:23.630 --> 00:02:25.120
You're making tradeoffs.

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:28.350
And at a certain point, you
make enough of those iterations

00:02:28.350 --> 00:02:30.490
that you decide, OK, it's time.

00:02:30.490 --> 00:02:32.660
Let's hand it off to engineers.

00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:35.424
So you hand it off to engineers,
and in a couple of weeks,

00:02:35.424 --> 00:02:37.840
or depending on the size of
the product you're working on,

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:40.910
maybe a few months, you
finally get this demo.

00:02:40.910 --> 00:02:42.910
And you get this
demo in your hands,

00:02:42.910 --> 00:02:46.180
and finally, your eyes
kind of start to light up,

00:02:46.180 --> 00:02:49.640
and the conversation starts
to change a little bit.

00:02:49.640 --> 00:02:51.400
All of a sudden,
we're not focused

00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:53.650
on the pixels that were
off on the projector,

00:02:53.650 --> 00:02:56.120
but we're talking about
the flow in our hands,

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:58.670
and we're having a productive
conversation at this point.

00:02:58.670 --> 00:03:02.600
And unfortunately, sometimes
at that point in the process,

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.440
you might realize a
lot of those decisions

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:06.600
you made weren't as
good as you thought.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:08.642
And it's expensive to make
changes at this point.

00:03:08.642 --> 00:03:10.016
You've made a lot
of assumptions.

00:03:10.016 --> 00:03:11.470
You've built this whole thing.

00:03:11.470 --> 00:03:13.420
It sucks to have
to go back on that.

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:16.220
And I've actually seen this
happen all the time at Google,

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:17.595
and it's something
we're actually

00:03:17.595 --> 00:03:19.569
trying to work on and
get a lot better at.

00:03:19.569 --> 00:03:21.610
And fortunately, we can,
because today, again, we

00:03:21.610 --> 00:03:23.730
have these new
tools that allow us

00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:26.820
to skip to the field
part a lot sooner.

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:29.870
And I think even without
like a CS degree or staring

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:32.680
at kind of a monospaced
wall of text,

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:34.270
we have these more
visual tools now,

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:37.650
and we can things interactive
in a matter of days

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:40.260
instead of waiting months, which
I think is really important.

00:03:40.260 --> 00:03:41.635
So thanks to a
lot of these tools

00:03:41.635 --> 00:03:44.760
like Form and Pixate and
Origami and Framer and Invision.

00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:48.530
We can hand around our devices
and ask people to try it,

00:03:48.530 --> 00:03:50.580
as opposed to just kind
of imagining and making

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:54.070
a lot of assumptions and filling
in the gaps in your own way.

00:03:54.070 --> 00:03:57.240
But even with all of the
different-- this explosion

00:03:57.240 --> 00:03:59.660
of all of these new
tools, there hasn't really

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:01.520
been a lot of
conversation about it.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:05.060
There hasn't even been really a
whole lot of press or articles

00:04:05.060 --> 00:04:05.760
on the subject.

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:07.986
I read one by Pasquale
D'Silva that felt pretty good,

00:04:07.986 --> 00:04:09.360
but it was one of
the only ones I

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:12.610
could find about these tools,
these interactive tools.

00:04:12.610 --> 00:04:14.486
And so we're really
excited to actually

00:04:14.486 --> 00:04:16.110
have a conversation
about these things,

00:04:16.110 --> 00:04:18.651
and I hope that inspires us to
continue to have conversations

00:04:18.651 --> 00:04:20.730
about the tools
that we use and how

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:24.080
it affects our process, how
it makes better products.

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:25.940
And so to start
this conversation,

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:28.820
