00:12:57.780 --> 00:13:01.210
were [INAUDIBLE] looked at as
kind of academic approaches

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:05.160
to design, like usability
testing and real user testing

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:07.590
and some of the things
that people tend to do when

00:13:07.590 --> 00:13:08.505
a product's already
been launched,

00:13:08.505 --> 00:13:10.879
and they're trying to figure
out what to do with it next.

00:13:10.879 --> 00:13:13.990
People were doing that
during the design process.

00:13:13.990 --> 00:13:17.480
And people were engaging their
end users, their stakeholders,

00:13:17.480 --> 00:13:19.560
and the multiple
networks of stakeholders.

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:22.820
Not only like the main
product leads, but also

00:13:22.820 --> 00:13:25.850
real users, and VPs,
and domain experts.

00:13:25.850 --> 00:13:27.890
And we needed a
place that allowed

00:13:27.890 --> 00:13:30.020
all of that
conversation to happen,

00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:32.980
and we needed a really
low investment way

00:13:32.980 --> 00:13:36.760
for the product to iterate and
to evolve in a process of kind

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:39.987
of design discovery
in reaction to that.

00:13:39.987 --> 00:13:41.820
So we wanted to make
sure that whatever tool

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:45.665
we built required very little
investment from the designer

00:13:45.665 --> 00:13:47.830
and was extremely flexible
the whole way through

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:49.870
so that the story could
really come through.

00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:51.180
NOAH LEVIN: Yeah, I think
