00:14:15.100 --> 00:14:17.480
able to prototype faster.

00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:19.310
So the next thing
I want to ask is

00:14:19.310 --> 00:14:21.280
why did it take up until now?

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:24.570
Honestly, I think even like
three years ago, at most,

00:14:24.570 --> 00:14:27.270
people might have prototyped a
little bit with some web code,

00:14:27.270 --> 00:14:30.010
or maybe used Keynote, and I
think a lot of people still do.

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:32.570
But a lot of the tools that
you guys represent up here

00:14:32.570 --> 00:14:33.640
are pretty new.

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:37.680
And what do we think took
so long to make that happen?

00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:39.682
I know, Paul, you had
some thoughts on this.

00:14:39.682 --> 00:14:43.016
PAUL COLTON: Yeah, actually
we were chatting last night

00:14:43.016 --> 00:14:44.640
or this morning--
it's all a blur now--

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:48.690
but the idea is how can
it be that all of a sudden

00:14:48.690 --> 00:14:50.160
we're all here on stage?

00:14:50.160 --> 00:14:52.650
I didn't know about these
guys when I started.

00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:53.370
I mean seriously.

00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:56.140
And I mean it's awfully
interesting that how could

00:14:56.140 --> 00:14:59.120
we have all these different
ways of prototyping

00:14:59.120 --> 00:15:01.740
and all converge to this
point in this room today?

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:03.670
And I rewound, and I
thought about everything,

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:06.180
and long story short
is I think it had a lot

00:15:06.180 --> 00:15:10.180
to do with the whole skeumorphic
shift to flat design.

00:15:10.180 --> 00:15:13.020
If you think about it, we
all spend all this time

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:15.540
nudging a pixel to get
that perfect texture,

00:15:15.540 --> 00:15:18.170
or that perfect shadow,
or whatever it might be.

00:15:18.170 --> 00:15:21.900
And frankly, how
the user interacted

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:25.860
with that perfect look,
if you will, came second.

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:29.310
I think when Apple kind
of threw that out frankly,

00:15:29.310 --> 00:15:31.480
shifted to let's
keep things flat,

00:15:31.480 --> 00:15:33.800
but now let's focus on the
experience a little more--

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:37.280
the motion and the actual
interaction-- all of a sudden

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:38.710
that put it front and center.

00:15:38.710 --> 00:15:42.550
So it's no coincidence that
for us, when we went out,

00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:43.640
that was the pain point.

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:45.490
No one said to me,
how do I make a better

00:15:45.490 --> 00:15:47.120
texture for my mobile app?

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:48.280
That was gone.

00:15:48.280 --> 00:15:52.780
What came to me is, how do I
get this nuanced interaction

00:15:52.780 --> 00:15:56.590
completely, precisely
how I want it to be,

00:15:56.590 --> 00:15:59.370
and how do I do that without
investing a lot of time

00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:01.380
in engineering and
design, frankly?

00:16:01.380 --> 00:16:05.230
Or at least can I iterate
my design of the interaction

00:16:05.230 --> 00:16:06.362
many times over?

00:16:06.362 --> 00:16:08.070
Because I always like
to say, by the way,

00:16:08.070 --> 00:16:09.300
designers like to iterate.

00:16:09.300 --> 00:16:10.110
They need to.

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:11.562
Engineers do not.

00:16:11.562 --> 00:16:13.770
They do not want to rewrite
their code over and over,

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:16.312
and I think that's fundamentally
the big shift, basically.

00:16:16.312 --> 00:16:17.770
BRANDON WALKIN:
Yeah, I don't know.

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:18.478
It's interesting.

00:16:18.478 --> 00:16:21.920
