this big canvas in something

00:22:01.130 --> 00:22:03.470
like Sketch or Photoshop,
you have almost a blank page,

00:22:03.470 --> 00:22:04.670
and you can create anything.

00:22:04.670 --> 00:22:06.920
But with that comes a little
bit of hesitation, right?

00:22:06.920 --> 00:22:09.380
Everyone has that little
bit of blank page,

00:22:09.380 --> 00:22:10.989
you just don't know
where to start.

00:22:10.989 --> 00:22:13.280
And actually I'm excited by
the contrast on this panel,

00:22:13.280 --> 00:22:16.530
because I find something
like Invision, for example,

00:22:16.530 --> 00:22:17.940
there are more
constraints to it.

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:19.660
There's a little bit
more-- if you've used it,

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:21.618
it's a little bit simpler
for you to get going.

00:22:21.618 --> 00:22:24.457
There's not the same kinds
of questions from customers

00:22:24.457 --> 00:22:26.040
that I've heard about
that are saying,

00:22:26.040 --> 00:22:27.830
I don't know how to
start with this tool.

00:22:27.830 --> 00:22:29.760
But on the other
hand, how does that

00:22:29.760 --> 00:22:31.040
affect what you can create?

00:22:31.040 --> 00:22:33.390
This one, for example,
you can tie together

00:22:33.390 --> 00:22:35.340
screens a lot
easier, and you can

00:22:35.340 --> 00:22:38.180
allow things to slide left
and right or up and down.

00:22:38.180 --> 00:22:40.610
How have you found the
approach of having a simpler,

00:22:40.610 --> 00:22:43.402
approachable tool versus
a more flexible one?

00:22:43.402 --> 00:22:45.360
CLARK VALBERG: I think
I look at product design

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:47.252
as being three
different dimensions.

00:22:47.252 --> 00:22:48.710
So there's the
aesthetic dimension,

00:22:48.710 --> 00:22:52.050
the interactive dimension,
and then there's the story.

00:22:52.050 --> 00:22:54.950
So with any of these
products, the focus

00:22:54.950 --> 00:22:58.250
of the product kind of
biases you towards a focus

00:22:58.250 --> 00:23:00.200
on one of those dimensions.

00:23:00.200 --> 00:23:02.616
So with Invision,
the focus is story.

00:23:02.616 --> 00:23:03.740
We all agree on aesthetics.

00:23:03.740 --> 00:23:05.554
I think we're not
wire forming tools,

00:23:05.554 --> 00:23:07.220
so we all agree that
you need aesthetics

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:10.630
to be able to have a broad
reach with your user engagement.

00:23:10.630 --> 00:23:13.580
But if the story is
why the user showed up,

00:23:13.580 --> 00:23:17.229
and the story is where you
want to bring them in the end,

00:23:17.229 --> 00:23:18.770
I look at that as
being fundamentally

00:23:18.770 --> 00:23:21.620
different than engineering
an interaction, which

00:23:21.620 --> 00:23:22.820
I think is also important.

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:24.278
But I think it's
something that has

00:23:24.278 --> 00:23:28.742
to happen after the story has
been nailed down, because most

00:23:28.742 --> 00:23:30.450
of the business
strategy, which is really

00:23:30.450 --> 00:23:34.319
what we do as designers, and
I think this also conspires

00:23:34.319 --> 00:23:36.610
with the whole changing role
of designers and designers

00:23:36.610 --> 00:23:38.270
just doing more,
being more involved,

00:23:38.270 --> 00:23:41.700
and taking a greater leadership
role in the product design

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:45.090
process, and even a
strategic business level.

00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:46.700
But when you're
there, and you're

00:23:46.700 --> 00:23:49.030
thinking about what
the business needs,

00:23:49.030 --> 00:23:51.620
the story has to be primary.

00:23:51.620 --> 00:23:56.840
The interactions are there as an
accompaniment to the aesthetics

00:23:56.840 --> 00:24:00.960
to create comfort as the
user responds to the system.

00:24:00.960 --> 00:24:03.090
Which is also important.

00:24:03.090 --> 00:24:05.270
PAUL COLTON: I just wanted
to add, from our take,

00:24:05.270 --> 00:24:08.760
I don't think-- you
don't require complexity

00:24:08.760 --> 00:24:13.000
to build something complex,
and I think, think of a pencil.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:14.920
It gives you complete
creative freedom.

00:24:14.920 --> 00:24:17.340
Yeah, it's one of the
simplest tools you could have.

00:24:17.340 --> 00:24:19.680
I think for us, that's
been our approach.

00:24:19.680 --> 00:24:23.560
How can we build the
absolute simplest tool

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:27.685
to then also absolutely
not hamper any creativity?

00:24:27.685 --> 00:24:29.310
And to touch a little
bit on your point

00:24:29.310 --> 00:24:31.320
too, I think also
for all of us, is

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:34.780
I think we strive-- I'll speak
for everyone, at least we do--

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:38.320
we strive that our tool
doesn't influence what

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:40.250
the final product's
going to be like.

00:24:40.250 --> 00:24:41.770
That's when we
know we've failed.

00:24:41.770 --> 00:24:44.640
If everything you build looks
like it was built in Pixate,

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:46.237
then we've done something wrong.

00:24:46.237 --> 00:24:48.570
We want to make sure that the
end result looks like what

00:24:48.570 --> 00:24:50.990
you wanted to build,
and we were just

00:24:50.990 --> 00:24:53.507
that pencil that made it happen.

00:24:53.507 --> 00:24:55.965
ADAM DEBRECZENI: Just to add
on to Brandon's point-- sorry,

00:24:55.965 --> 00:24:58.280
I cut you off, Koen.

00:24:58.280 --> 00:24:59.960
One of the big things
that we focused

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:01.550
on with the open
canvas, the fact

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:05.382
that you can build
anything, is it's

00:25:05.382 --> 00:25:06.590
a great amount of difficulty.

00:25:06.590 --> 00:25:08.685
So you first open up
Form-- blank canvas.

00:25:08.685 --> 00:25:11.410
It's really intimidating.

00:25:11.410 --> 00:25:13.910
The main thing that we focused
on while designing patches

00:25:13.910 --> 00:25:18.240
is how do we make this the most
consistent system possible?

00:25:18.240 --> 00:25:20.010
And because everything
is consistent,

00:25:20.010 --> 00:25:22.100
there's only outputs
and only inputs,

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:23.880
data flow is always
the same way,

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:26.690
you can build a lot
of reusable chunks.

00:25:26.690 --> 00:25:28.460
So you can build
your own patches.

00:25:28.460 --> 00:25:30.750
And because you can
reuse a lot of it,

00:25:30.750 --> 00:25:32.490
and you can build
your own patches,

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:35.110
the canvas actually
ends up shrinking a lot.

00:25:35.110 --> 00:25:37.490
Because it's actually
a very concise canvas,

00:25:37.490 --> 00:25:39.520
it makes it very easy to parse.

00:25:39.520 --> 00:25:44.212
And because it's parsable,
you can actually-- well,

00:25:44.212 --> 00:25:45.670
because you can
build anything, you

00:25:45.670 --> 00:25:47.586
can actually build like
a hamburger menu patch

00:25:47.586 --> 00:25:49.270
if you really wanted to.

00:25:49.270 --> 00:25:50.950
And it's still made
out of the same 20

00:25:50.950 --> 00:25:53.050
patches that Form ships with.

00:25:53.050 --> 00:25:53.690
NOAH LEVIN: One
thing that's starting

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:55.064
to come up that
I'm curious about

00:25:55.064 --> 00:25:57.690
is Clark had
mentioned that there's

00:25:57.690 --> 00:26:00.960
a big emphasis in
Invision for storytelling,

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:02.790
and at other points
of our conversation

00:26:02.790 --> 00:26:04.850
here, we're talking
a bit about moments

00:26:04.850 --> 00:26:06.950
of openness and execution.

00:26:06.950 --> 00:26:10.320
Is there a point in the process,
in the design process, that you

00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:12.410
think your tool is
meant to be used in?

00:26:12.410 --> 00:26:13.580
Can it be used at any point?

00:26:13.580 --> 00:26:17.650
Are your tools all possible for
storytelling in a higher level?

00:26:17.650 --> 00:26:20.730
Is it just about execution
polish and detail?

00:26:20.730 --> 00:26:22.350
KOEN BOK: Well,
I think that ties

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:24.080
into the flexibility
of your tool.

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:26.780
So for example, if you would
take the linear approach

00:26:26.780 --> 00:26:29.190
for any of these tools, you
would be pretty much confined

00:26:29.190 --> 00:26:31.950
in this one thing, like
this microinteraction.

00:26:31.950 --> 00:26:36.660
But once you get to code or
visual or signal flow program,

00:26:36.660 --> 00:26:37.620
you can do anything.

00:26:37.620 --> 00:26:41.700
So it's pretty-- like in Framer,
it's really-- it's not easy,

00:26:41.700 --> 00:26:44.420
but it's doable to set
up really huge apps,

00:26:44.420 --> 00:26:46.650
basically build entire
applications in there.

00:26:46.650 --> 00:26:51.720
So for us I think
we often get defined

00:26:51.720 --> 00:26:53.674
as sort of like a
microinteraction tool,

00:26:53.674 --> 00:26:55.340
because you focus on
these small things.

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:58.006
But it's actually, I think we're
one of the few tools where it's

00:26:58.006 --> 00:27:02.150
possible to build out
entire app experiences.

00:27:02.150 --> 00:27:03.276
BRANDON WALKIN: Go for it.

00:27:03.276 --> 00:27:03.960
Oh, OK.

00:27:03.960 --> 00:27:04.460
Yeah.

00:27:04.460 --> 00:27:07.830
So at Facebook at
least, we started

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:11.260
using Quartz Composer
really early in the process.

00:27:11.260 --> 00:27:15.580
And so whether it's like a new
app that we're thinking about,

00:27:15.580 --> 00:27:18.360
when we go and
pitch this to Mark,

00:27:18.360 --> 00:27:22.170
he's expecting to see a full
prototype that is polished,

00:27:22.170 --> 00:27:24.610
that has animations,
that has interactions,

00:27:24.610 --> 00:27:26.730
that's thought through.

00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:29.540
And obviously
sketching plays a role.

00:27:29.540 --> 00:27:32.140
We all have
sketchbooks and draw.

00:27:32.140 --> 00:27:35.730
It's very low
friction to do that,

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:39.980
but yeah, I think it really
does help tell the story when

00:27:39.980 --> 00:27:43.200
the thing that you're showing
looks like how it will actually

00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:44.837
look to users.

00:27:44.837 --> 00:27:46.670
CLARK VALBERG: I think
a pretty major caveat

00:27:46.670 --> 00:27:50.140
there is that investment
is the enemy of creativity.

00:27:50.140 --> 00:27:53.130
The more you invest in any
particular direction, the more

00:27:53.130 --> 00:27:56.890
biased, naturally, you
are to moving ever further

00:27:56.890 --> 00:27:58.379
in that direction.

00:27:58.379 --> 00:28:00.420
So when you're dealing
with these multiple layers

00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:02.005
of abstraction, you
have your design,

00:28:02.005 --> 00:28:03.590
then you have your
interactive components,

00:28:03.590 --> 00:28:06.215
and maybe you have two different
tools, so you're in Photoshop,

00:28:06.215 --> 00:28:07.770
and you're in one
of these tools.

00:28:07.770 --> 00:28:09.270
You have to be very
careful that you

00:28:09.270 --> 00:28:10.750
don't end up down a rabbit hole.

00:28:10.750 --> 00:28:12.720
It just makes you either
personally resistant

00:28:12.720 --> 00:28:14.980
to the change that
you'd like to make,

00:28:14.980 --> 00:28:18.510
or the changes that happen as a
natural process of discovering

00:28:18.510 --> 00:28:20.330
what the user really needs.

00:28:20.330 --> 00:28:22.770
And I think that there's
also a really important

00:28:22.770 --> 00:28:26.140
philosophical difference between
articulation and discovery.

00:28:26.140 --> 00:28:29.437
So if you have an
idea, if we took,

00:28:29.437 --> 00:28:31.020
let's say Facebook
Paper or something,

00:28:31.020 --> 00:28:34.260
and we knew that we wanted
to take that animation

00:28:34.260 --> 00:28:36.680
and design it, to engineer
it, to make it look exactly

00:28:36.680 --> 00:28:39.620
like that with all the
subtle nuances, that's

00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:40.860
a certain process.

00:28:40.860 --> 00:28:43.640
That's a certain domain.

00:28:43.640 --> 00:28:46.310
If you're not sure
what you want, and you

00:28:46.310 --> 00:28:48.420
know that the user
came from point A,

00:28:48.420 --> 00:28:50.504
and they're ending
up at point Z,

00:28:50.504 --> 00:28:52.670
and there are all these
different points in between,

00:28:52.670 --> 00:28:54.580
and you want to
understand how to deal

00:28:54.580 --> 00:28:58.460
with the gentle volley of
interaction with that user,

00:28:58.460 --> 00:29:02.190
I think that you need to stay
really flexible, because three

00:29:02.190 --> 00:29:04.200
screens in your app
could turn into one.

00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:05.800
Or one screen could
turn into three,

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:08.750
depending on the direction
that you make strategically.

00:29:08.750 --> 00:29:09.990
NOAH LEVIN: Yeah.

00:29:09.990 --> 00:29:11.430
I'm going to move things
along just a little bit,

00:29:11.430 --> 00:29:13.680
just so we can make sure we
touch on one of the topics

00:29:13.680 --> 00:29:15.435
that I think we
talked to be about one

00:29:15.435 --> 00:29:18.170
of the most interesting
things we look at

00:29:18.170 --> 00:29:19.820
is where is this really going?

00:29:19.820 --> 00:29:22.070
Is it going to be
one of these tools

00:29:22.070 --> 00:29:23.750
that we end up
using predominately

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:25.530
in the same way you
could argue something

00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:27.210
like Photoshop or
Sketch is done?

00:29:27.210 --> 00:29:29.980
There's not a huge amount
of disparity in the tools

00:29:29.980 --> 00:29:33.119
we've used in other contexts,
yet here these tools

00:29:33.119 --> 00:29:33.910
are very different.

00:29:33.910 --> 00:29:36.820
And you have a lot of choice
now, and in some ways,

00:29:36.820 --> 00:29:39.820
you can almost find that
paralyzing as a way to start.

00:29:39.820 --> 00:29:45.110
And so just as kind of a
final topic to touch on ,

00:29:45.110 --> 00:29:48.420
let's start with, is it
going to be one tool?

00:29:48.420 --> 00:29:51.445
Do you think that it's just
one of us standing after this

00:29:51.445 --> 00:29:52.820
or something, and
it's just going

00:29:52.820 --> 00:29:54.255
to be one tool you
approach, or is it

00:29:54.255 --> 00:29:55.505
a combination of these things?

00:29:55.505 --> 00:29:57.640
Can you use these
things together?

00:29:57.640 --> 00:29:58.140
Yeah.

00:29:58.140 --> 00:30:00.582
Where do we think this
is going in that sense?

00:30:00.582 --> 00:30:02.040
KOEN BOK: I think
it's good to have

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:03.750
choice, finally, as designers.

00:30:03.750 --> 00:30:07.680
We've been coming
from five to 10 years

00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:10.690
where if you were designing, you
were probably using Photoshop,

00:30:10.690 --> 00:30:13.290
and everybody around
was using Photoshop.

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:19.114
So I'm pretty happy
to get rid of that,

00:30:19.114 --> 00:30:20.530
although Photoshop
is a nice tool.

00:30:20.530 --> 00:30:24.920
But I'm also pretty sure that
all the different directions--

00:30:24.920 --> 00:30:27.460
like it's weird that we all
have such different approaches,

00:30:27.460 --> 00:30:30.790
like from UI-based to
visual programming to like

00:30:30.790 --> 00:30:32.000
actual codes.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:34.650
And I think the real
tool in the future

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:36.530
will probably be a
blend of some of those

00:30:36.530 --> 00:30:39.100
in a really smart balance,
where maybe you give up

00:30:39.100 --> 00:30:42.530
some flexibility for a
really low learning curve,

00:30:42.530 --> 00:30:44.160
or maybe not at all.

00:30:44.160 --> 00:30:45.000
We'll see.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:48.830
But I would definitely be
surprised if in five years,

00:30:48.830 --> 00:30:51.630
we would still be debating
if visual program would

00:30:51.630 --> 00:30:54.060
be better than code
or better than a UI.

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:55.587
That will solve
itself over time.

00:30:55.587 --> 00:30:57.670
BRANDON WALKIN: I actually
do think designers will

00:30:57.670 --> 00:31:01.290
be expected to know
prototyping tools.

00:31:01.290 --> 00:31:02.390
KOEN BOK: [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:02.390 --> 00:31:04.056
BRANDON WALKIN: Just
like every designer

00:31:04.056 --> 00:31:06.270
is expected to know
Photoshop or Sketch,

00:31:06.270 --> 00:31:07.870
and designers are
really good at that.

00:31:07.870 --> 00:31:09.328
Like you can go on
Dribble, and you

00:31:09.328 --> 00:31:12.770
can see a whole range of
different types of visuals,

00:31:12.770 --> 00:31:14.230
right?

00:31:14.230 --> 00:31:17.920
You're actually not seeing
that with interaction.

00:31:17.920 --> 00:31:20.690
What you normally see
is people will be really

00:31:20.690 --> 00:31:23.070
creative with visuals,
because they know how

00:31:23.070 --> 00:31:25.290
to use those tools,
but then when it

00:31:25.290 --> 00:31:27.120
comes to how the app
is actually structured

00:31:27.120 --> 00:31:29.420
and the specific
interactions, they'll

00:31:29.420 --> 00:31:33.250
pull stuff from some applets
out there and maybe another app,

00:31:33.250 --> 00:31:34.720
combine them together.

00:31:34.720 --> 00:31:37.810
But you really don't see
the same sort of creativity

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:39.040
in interactions.

00:31:39.040 --> 00:31:42.390
And so I think once people start
learning these new interaction

00:31:42.390 --> 00:31:44.680
tools, and once they
become more advanced,

00:31:44.680 --> 00:31:46.840
easier to learn,
easier to use, I

00:31:46.840 --> 00:31:48.827
think that's going to be huge.

00:31:48.827 --> 00:31:50.910
ADAM DEBRECZENI: And if
you really think about it,

00:31:50.910 --> 00:31:52.951
we've been talking and
interacting with computers

00:31:52.951 --> 00:31:54.310
the same way for like 30 years.

00:31:54.310 --> 00:31:56.370
It's been [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:56.370 --> 00:31:58.660
They've been talking back
to us through consoles.

00:31:58.660 --> 00:32:01.490
And there's been
almost a sense of dogma

00:32:01.490 --> 00:32:04.352
laid down with how we
actually build things.

00:32:04.352 --> 00:32:06.810
And for the first time, we're
actually empowering designers

00:32:06.810 --> 00:32:11.800
to go out and essentially make
their designs interactive,

00:32:11.800 --> 00:32:14.080
and we have no dogma right now.

00:32:14.080 --> 00:32:15.570
So it's really
fascinating that we

00:32:15.570 --> 00:32:18.390
have Wiziwig,
visual programming,

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:20.267
and textual-based programming.

00:32:20.267 --> 00:32:22.600
It's interesting right now
that we have no expectations,

00:32:22.600 --> 00:32:25.350
so I think that's why there's
all these different directions.

00:32:25.350 --> 00:32:26.120
CLARK VALBERG: I
think the thing that's

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:28.280
going to precipitate
all of this change

00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:30.100
is the changing role
of the designer.

00:32:30.100 --> 00:32:32.625
So I think we've seen a
convergence around everybody

00:32:32.625 --> 00:32:34.750
just generally describing
themselves as a designer,

00:32:34.750 --> 00:32:36.916
because nobody wanted to
be just a UX person or just

00:32:36.916 --> 00:32:38.490
a visual person.

00:32:38.490 --> 00:32:40.942
I see in the future, and
I see this happening now,

00:32:40.942 --> 00:32:43.150
even companies in this room,
where you have a product

00:32:43.150 --> 00:32:47.090
designer, who really thinks
more like a product manager.

00:32:47.090 --> 00:32:50.000
And I think product managers
that also think like designers,

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.560
and I think best of
both will probably

00:32:52.560 --> 00:32:55.630
have that kind of mindset--
strategically-driven, needs

00:32:55.630 --> 00:32:58.105
of the business
at the forefront.

00:32:58.105 --> 00:32:59.480
Leadership skills--
understanding

00:32:59.480 --> 00:33:02.110
how to engage end users, how
to take a lot of feedback

00:33:02.110 --> 00:33:04.360
and sort it, and throw away
the stuff that isn't good,

00:33:04.360 --> 00:33:06.820
but interpret it emphatically.

00:33:06.820 --> 00:33:08.810
And then, perhaps,
people who are more

00:33:08.810 --> 00:33:13.832
focused on the interactive
layer, the more subtle nuances

00:33:13.832 --> 00:33:15.540
of an application,
and I see those people

00:33:15.540 --> 00:33:19.975
sitting in the room as
part of an ecosystem of how

00:33:19.975 --> 00:33:23.690
a product is designed in an
open, kind of socialized way.

00:33:23.690 --> 00:33:26.990
What I don't see is the
traditional hand-off process

00:33:26.990 --> 00:33:29.517
where a designer or a few
designers go into a room,

00:33:29.517 --> 00:33:31.100
they build something,
and then there's

00:33:31.100 --> 00:33:33.390
this cadence of design review.

00:33:33.390 --> 00:33:36.300
I think that humped
design review

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:38.080
cadence will flatten out.

00:33:38.080 --> 00:33:40.490
And the design that's
being worked on

00:33:40.490 --> 00:33:43.430
will be socialized
and more available

00:33:43.430 --> 00:33:46.940
and engaged beyond
the design department,

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:49.472
kind of through the life of the
product development process.

00:33:49.472 --> 00:33:50.180
NOAH LEVIN: Yeah.

00:33:50.180 --> 00:33:51.721
It's even interesting
how these tools

00:33:51.721 --> 00:33:53.330
might affect our
role in that process

00:33:53.330 --> 00:33:54.980
and change the
pieces in which we're

00:33:54.980 --> 00:33:57.320
involved throughout that cycle.

