00:37:39.680 --> 00:37:42.830
that's descriptive at a
programmatic level of the thing

00:37:42.830 --> 00:37:45.810
that you see on the screen,
how that ties together--

00:37:45.810 --> 00:37:46.600
frameworks.

00:37:46.600 --> 00:37:48.550
I mean there's probably at least
some developers in the room,

00:37:48.550 --> 00:37:49.130
right?

00:37:49.130 --> 00:37:51.949
It is way more complicated
than just generating code.

00:37:51.949 --> 00:37:53.490
All of this has to
be glued together.

00:37:53.490 --> 00:37:54.830
There has to be
some infrastructure

00:37:54.830 --> 00:37:57.090
to tie it all together, and
that takes hard decisions.

00:37:57.090 --> 00:38:01.360
And even how that happens is a
very rapidly evolving process.

00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:03.400
I mean it's a whole field.

00:38:03.400 --> 00:38:05.650
And so I think it would be
really difficult for a tool

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:07.532
to generate an app
you could ship.

00:38:07.532 --> 00:38:08.990
And I think that'll
probably be a--

00:38:08.990 --> 00:38:10.360
BRANDON WALKIN: I think there
are all these complexities

00:38:10.360 --> 00:38:11.680
that you have to deal
with when you're building

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:14.369
an app, versus what you actually
want to be thinking about when

00:38:14.369 --> 00:38:15.160
you're prototyping.

00:38:15.160 --> 00:38:17.540
For example, when
you're prototyping,

00:38:17.540 --> 00:38:19.920
it may not be worth
the effort to make

00:38:19.920 --> 00:38:22.740
sure your prototype works
in every single language

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:24.899
or on every single screen size.

00:38:24.899 --> 00:38:26.440
That's going to take
a bunch of time,

00:38:26.440 --> 00:38:28.940
and if it's not going to help
you solve the problem that you

00:38:28.940 --> 00:38:31.380
were originally trying to
solve, you don't want to do it.

00:38:31.380 --> 00:38:34.941
I think in addition
to that, when

00:38:34.941 --> 00:38:36.690
you're building apps--
say you're building

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:39.100
an app for iOS--
you probably want

00:38:39.100 --> 00:38:40.800
to use the system frameworks.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:43.144
You want to use UI kit.

00:38:43.144 --> 00:38:44.560
That gives you a
bunch of benefits

00:38:44.560 --> 00:38:48.340
like it's immediately
accessible if you're

00:38:48.340 --> 00:38:51.280
visually impaired
or hearing impaired.

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:53.040
The Apple just kind of work.

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:55.850
And I think if
the tool just sort

00:38:55.850 --> 00:38:59.040
of renders in its
own environment,

00:38:59.040 --> 00:39:00.985
you're going to miss
out on a lot of that.

00:39:00.985 --> 00:39:01.610
KOEN BOK: Yeah.

00:39:01.610 --> 00:39:04.140
And having said that, I
also-- I'm with Brandon.

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:07.260
I think that it's too big and
probably the wrong problem

00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:09.160
to tackle to go
from your prototype

00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:10.589
to the final product at once.

00:39:10.589 --> 00:39:13.130
But there's a lot of in-between
that we can actually improve,

00:39:13.130 --> 00:39:13.630
I feel.

00:39:13.630 --> 00:39:15.760
I think a lot of you are
still sending ZIP files

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:17.936
